ted@nmsu.edu (Ted Dunning) writes:


>In article <C4tnGu.4Bn@cs.uiuc.edu> kadie@cs.uiuc.edu (Carl M Kadie) writes:

>   >	Is forcing someone to hand over the keys to one's hard disk
>   >forcing someone to incriminate themself?
>   [...]

>   Mike Godwin of the EFF talked about this at his workshop at CPF '93.
>   If I remember him correctly, he said that the courts would probably
>   not consider an order to disclose keys as self-incrimination.
>   (whether they *should* is a different question.)



>how is forcing somebody to hand over keys to their hard drive any
>different from forcing them to hand over keys to the filing cabinet?

>if there is a warrant, then handing over the keys is required, and if
>there isn't, then it shouldn't be required.

The key to a filing cabinet is a physical object; the "key" to decrypting
the hard disk is a piece of data.  In particular it might be a sentence
like "I blew up the world trade center on <date>".  So you might
not be able to reveal it without incriminating yourself.
